issue_body:
For the example model:
```
module test {
  namespace "http://example.com";
  prefix "test";

  extension ext1;
  extension ext2;

  list l {
    key "k";
    test:ext1;
    test:ext2;
 
    leaf k {
      type int32;
    }
  }
}
```
with the following test.xml:
```
<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<data xmlns="urn:ietf:params:xml:ns:netconf:base:1.0">
  <l xmlns="http://example.com">
    <k>10</k>
  </l>
</data>
```
I get the following error:
```
> yang2dsdl -d . -t data -v test.xml test.yang
== Generating RELAX NG schema './test-data.rng'
Done.

== Generating Schematron schema './test-data.sch'
Done.

== Generating DSRL schema './test-data.dsrl'
Done.

== Validating grammar and datatypes ...
./test-data.rng:2: element interleave: Relax-NG parser error : Element interleave is empty
Relax-NG schema ./test-data.rng failed to compile
```
Problem seems to be that the generated test-data.rng contains an empty interleave element, which according with with RelaxNG, must have children.
Most likely the presence of 2 extensions next to the key that is causing this problem.
Not reproducible with one single extension, or with the extensions outside the list, or by having a container instead of list. Adding an additional leaf to the list removes the error.

